---
import Base from '../../layouts/Base.astro';
import { highlightKai } from '../../lib/highlight';
import { links } from '../../lib/links';

const helloSnippet = `fn main() {
  println("hello, kaikai")
}`;
const helloHtml = await highlightKai(helloSnippet);
---

<Base title="Get started · kaikai" lang="en">
  <article class="get-started-page">
    <div class="container">
      <header>
        <p class="eyebrow">Get started</p>
        <h1>Installing kaikai</h1>
        <p class="lead">
          The command-line tool is called <code>kai</code>. You can
          install it via Homebrew (quick) or build it from source (if
          you want to contribute to the language).
        </p>
      </header>

      <section>
        <h2>Homebrew &middot; macOS and Linux</h2>
        <p>
          The official distribution lives in its own tap.
        </p>
<pre><code>brew install kaikailang-org/kaikai/kaikai</code></pre>
        <p>Verify the install:</p>
<pre><code>kai --version</code></pre>
        <p>
          If <code>clang</code> is on your <code>PATH</code> (on macOS,
          run <code>xcode-select --install</code> to get the Xcode
          Command Line Tools), <code>kai</code> uses the LLVM backend by
          default. Otherwise it falls back to the C backend, which works
          on any machine with a standard <code>cc</code>.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section>
        <h2>From source</h2>
        <p>
          To hack on the compiler or track <code>main</code>, clone the
          repo and build the three-stage bootstrap:
        </p>
<pre><code>git clone {links.github.kaikai}
cd kaikai
make tier0</code></pre>
        <p>
          The first <code>./bin/kai</code> invocation compiles whichever
          stage binaries are missing; subsequent calls reuse them.
          Stages 0 and 1 only need a C99 <code>cc</code>; stage 2 is the
          user-facing path.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section>
        <h2>Your first program</h2>
        <p>Save this as <code>hello.kai</code>:</p>
        <div class="code-block" set:html={helloHtml} />
        <p>Then run it:</p>
<pre><code>kai run hello.kai
# hello, kaikai</code></pre>
        <p>To produce a native binary instead of running directly:</p>
<pre><code>kai build hello.kai -o hello
./hello</code></pre>
      </section>

      <section>
        <h2>What's next</h2>
        <ul class="nextsteps">
          <li>
            Browse the <a href="/en/examples">examples</a>.
          </li>
          <li>
            Read the <a href="/en/book">book</a> for the long-form
            walkthrough of the language with real programs.
          </li>
          <li>
            Visit the <a href={links.github.kaikai} rel="noopener">GitHub
            repo</a> and open an issue if something seems off.
          </li>
        </ul>
      </section>
    </div>
  </article>
</Base>

<style>
  .get-started-page {
    padding-block: var(--space-16) var(--space-12);
  }
  .eyebrow {
    color: var(--accent);
    font-size: 0.85rem;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    letter-spacing: 0.1em;
    margin-bottom: var(--space-2);
  }
  .get-started-page header {
    margin-bottom: var(--space-12);
  }
  .lead {
    font-family: var(--font-serif);
    font-size: 1.15rem;
    color: var(--fg-muted);
    max-width: 60ch;
    line-height: 1.6;
  }
  section {
    margin-top: var(--space-12);
    max-width: 70ch;
  }
  section h2 {
    margin-bottom: var(--space-4);
  }
  section p {
    font-family: var(--font-serif);
    font-size: 1.02rem;
    line-height: 1.65;
  }
  section pre {
    margin-block: var(--space-4) var(--space-6);
  }
  .code-block :global(pre.shiki) {
    background: var(--code-bg) !important;
    margin-block: var(--space-4) var(--space-6);
    padding: var(--space-4) var(--space-6);
    border-radius: var(--radius);
    overflow-x: auto;
    font-size: 0.88rem;
  }
  .nextsteps {
    list-style: none;
    padding: 0;
    margin: 0;
    font-family: var(--font-serif);
    font-size: 1.05rem;
    line-height: 1.8;
  }
  .nextsteps li::before {
    content: "›";
    color: var(--accent);
    margin-right: 0.6rem;
    font-weight: 700;
  }
</style>
